Yesterday I got the Johnson and Johnson vaccine. I was the last appointment, so they observed me for 5 minutes, and I left. After riding in the car for a few minutes, I noticed that I was having a hard time breathing and my throat felt like it was starting to swell. By that time, the clinic was closed, so I went to the emergency room just in case and sat in my car since they didn't allow people to sit in the waiting room because if covid.  It started becoming increasingly difficult to breathe, and I was feeling more and more swelling of my throat and tongue. I was having a lot of dizziness, nausea, facial flushing, palpitations, and some mild confusion. I then started getting numbness in the bottom half of my face. Over time, the numbness spread, mostly staying on the left side of my body (face, scalp, lower arms and legs, left side on tongue and inside of mouth). I also started getting a prickling burning pain sensation for brief periods of time where I had numbness. I had decided that if my breathing worsened at all, I would go to the er even though I can't afford it.   After about an hour and a half, my breathing started to feel less constricted and like there was less resistance. The swelling in my throat was mostly in the upper throat where I had difficulty swallowing but not as much difficulty breathing. The numbness continued to get worse and was sometimes disappearing and reappearing in the same spot.  At 9:30 pm we went to go get some benadryl. I continued feeling less and less swelling and having an easier time breathing. At that point, I went home. Once I was home, my breathing continued to improve and the numbness started to dissipate.  In the middle of the night, I started itching and getting widespread hives and getting a sharp burning pricking pain that would last a few seconds in different areas. The numbness also started coming back mostly in my face. I continued to have difficulty swallowing.  I am feeling much better today. I still feel some slight swelling in my throat when I swallow, but my breathing is fine. I'm still itchy and occasionally breaking out in hives. Im having mild lower facial numbness. I'm also starting to get the normal side effects of fever, headache, arm soreness, and body aches. I'm taking benadryl every 4 hours.
LAB_DATA: None. I did not go inside the er (I just sat in my car in the er parking lot) because I don't have health insurance.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 2nd Dose of Pfizer vaccine administered at 9:30 am on Saturday 3/6. Saturday afternoon through Sunday evening felt feverish, chills, body aches. Felt fine Monday morning. Monday about 11 am began to feel tightness in chest, thought it was bad heartburn. Pain kept me awake Monday night, and continued into Tuesday morning. Called the doctor, was sent to urgent care. Urgent care detected elevated tritonin and had me transported to the emergency room. Elevated heart rate and rising tritonin levels had me admitted to the hospital. Given heperin and a beta-blocker, given a CT scan, and monitored over night. On Wednesday had a echocardiogram and then a heart catherter and imaging, which showed a healthy heart, no plaque, no blockages. Tritonin levels and heart rate returned to normal. Released from hospital on evening of 3/10.
LAB_DATA: blood tests on 3/9 and 3/10 CT scan on 3/9 Echocardiogram and heart catherter on 3/10

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approximately 1 hr. and 45 minutes after receiving my first dose of the Moderna Vaccine I started to cough as if I was starting the initial phase of asthma. No difficulty breathing nor wheezing just a slight tightness in my bronchioles with the cough. I sat down took a cough drop had my asthma nebulizing treatment at hand if needed and a small oxygen canister , but didn't need if and symptom subsided about after an hour or so. Later that night at around  10 p.m. I started to get a headache went to bed, but at around 4 a.m. the next morning( now Saturday) the headache was getting worst so I inserted rectally a pediatric acetaminophen suppository. It helped a bit. At around 10 a.m. that morning the headache intensified so I took one Advil 200mg tablet and I felt better. My stomach started to bother me around 3 p.m. the same day so I took a Prilosec OTC tablet. The next morning Sunday I had a bit of a loomy headache so I took a Tylenol tablet first, it didn't help so about 2 hours after I took an Advil 200mg tablet, but it just helped slightly. At around 4:30 to 4:45pm on that Sunday I felt a strong pressure in the center of my chest, almost as if there was something blocking my airway and heart a bit. I went home and had a feeling of something traveling from my chest to my neck and head and a throbbing pain in my head. I took a shower and headed to the ER. I also had tingling and some numbness in my are and leg and face. by 2 a.m. the next morning I was discharged. The EKG was normal, no sign of heart attack nor stroke. I have a really bad headache still, some swelling under my left armpit and a low grade fever.
LAB_DATA: EKG, D-Dimer. Chest x-ray and other blood work
OTHER_MEDS: At the time of actual vaccination and right before vaccination NONE, but before (as in days before vaccination)  I had been taking the following: Advil tablets, Tylenol caplets, Prilosec OTC tablets, Pepcid AC chewable tablets, Biotin, Vita

This nerve pain was often felt in both legs as well. My daily walk became very difficult to do. The second week I began to have a vein pulsate in my right forearm and a tic developed in that area. This went on for three days. By the third week I started experiencing daily headaches.  My blood pressure increased in the third week to about 167/90 up from 136/80. Up until today, March 17 I still have mild headaches on and off, and some mild inner thigh nerve pain, and minimal stiffness and mild pain in both of my legs. She also reported a "dry throat" sensation, but denies throat tightness or itching and did not have any respiratory compromise for the hour that she remained under observation. Symptoms subsided and patient left the facility. Followed up with her later by phone to inform her that her immediate allergic reaction was a contraindication to her receiving the second Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine and that she should not return for a second appointment. Advised that she seek allergist consultation given her history of multiple allergies, and to determine whether there was a common substrate for any of them. Said that she could possibly consider the Johnson&Johnson vaccine thereafter, if she did not have any known allergies to components of it.

At approximately 08:45hrs on 15 March 2021, vaccinators in Booth 1 reported to the on-site Pharmacy that they were on their second patient of the day but had no vaccine in the multi-dose vial. A rapid investigation was completed, and it was determined that the first patient who visited that booth today had received a dose from a vial that was potentially left-over from the clinic last night. An immediate conference with site leadership was conducted. The patient was identified via computer database by encounter time stamp and confirmed by the vaccinator team. Extensive research and consultation were conducted by Dr., including contacting Pfizer for consultation, and reviewing information from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) including Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices (ACIP) recommendations.  Per the Pfizer document entitled Storage and Handling of DILUTED VIALS Outside of Recommendations in the EUA Prescribing Information DURING and AFTER DILUTION?: Pfizer has conducted physical and chemical stability studies which have shown that the vaccine maintains all its measured quality attributes when diluted vaccine is stored in the vial at 2ï¿½C to 30ï¿½C for up to a cumulative period of 18 hours, in addition to the routine/labelled in-use period [of 6 hours]. It was determined that immediate administration of another dose was not required based on this information. In addition, clinical studies had not been performed that examined reissuing an initial vaccine after receiving one handled outside of the Emergency Use Authorization recommendations. The patient is scheduled to return in three weeks for their second dose. The patient was contacted and advised of the situation, and questions and concerns addressed. Immediate changes were implemented to avoid exhausted vials from being near the pharmacy.   Background:  Vaccinators in the clinic are from multiple agencies and are providing support to Community Vaccination Center Programs. Vaccine is reconstituted in the pharmacy. This is a controlled booth. Vaccinators enter the pharmacy booth at a defined entrance location where they receive a pre-filled plastic bin containing syringes, needles, vaccine record cards, and vaccine. The vaccine they receive is a multi-dose vial containing six doses, which are drawn-up individually in front of the patient in the vaccination booths due to community trust issues previously identified. When the supplies/vaccine is exhausted, the vaccinator returns to the pharmacy booth with their bin containing just the empty vial. This vial is stored in a plastic bag on the pharmacy table based off of inherited practices. The bin is replenished, and the vaccinator returns to their respective vaccination booth.   Incident:  Around 08:45hrs on 15 March 2021 vaccinators in Booth 1 reported to the joint on-site Pharmacy and indicated that upon draw-up for their second patient there was no vaccine in the multi-dose vial.  Investigation:  Dr. immediately convened a conference with the pharmacists present in the pharmacy booth. They included a Pharmacist, and Commanders.  It was determined that the vial likely originated from the bag of empty vials contained in a bag which had overflowed onto the pharmacy table. The vial in question likely contained an extra dose that was not administered last night due to appointment no-shows. This yielded the concern that the dose that was administered had become inactivated due to time after reconstitution and temperature. The vaccine was reconstituted at approximately 19:00hrs last evening (14 Mar 2021) and was no longer temperature controlled after that time.  Dr. contacted the manufacturer, Pfizer, who identified that their research indicates the vaccine to be chemically intact over 18 hours after reconstitution if stored in the vial between 2-30 degrees Celsius; this being the case for this vial. Dr. conferenced with the pharmacists, compared information with the CDC guidelines, and developed consensus that readministering the first dose was not required given that all quality attributes were likely maintained per the Pfizer stability studies. Dr. then notified the patient of the conclusion and provided instruction to return at their scheduled appointment date in three weeks for their second dose. Patient reported no symptoms at the time.     Immediate Actions Taken:  Department of Health utilized their Database to determine the patient who received the inactivated dose.   Dr. contacted the vaccine manufacturer Pfizer   Dr. then contacted the patient,   Controls were altered to remove the exhausted vials from the pharmacy table.   Vaccinators were instructed to verify their vials for appropriate volume/dosages.  Notifications made to site.  Patient advised to return to clinic at scheduled appointment time in three weeks to receive second dose.  Conclusion: The new safety controls in place in the pharmacy will prevent future similar occurrences. This information will be pushed to all clinic personnel in the form of a safety briefing to acknowledge the misstep and create awareness to decrease chances of future events. The patient was not harmed in this event and has received guidance from Dr. after review of manufacturer and CDC information.

The patient quickly recovered and stated he felt fine but embarrassed and wanted to call his wife and go home. I started feeling subtle flu-like symptoms about 6 hours after receiving shot. At first I thought it was in my head but by the early evening I felt like I had a full blown fever even though I never actually had a fever at any point.  I had chills, muscles aches, head aches, and extreme fatigue. My back hurt especially and overall I felt very weak. I also had pain at the injection site that got worse the following day. I had trouble even lifting my arm to reach a drink just a few feet away from me.  The arm soreness lasted through the Monday following my vaccination (I received it on a Friday). All my symptoms were at their worst on Saturday. I felt much better on Sunday but still had the arm pain through Monday. Motrin did help relieve the worst my symptoms. I thought that was the end of my symptoms but that last week I have noticed what I believe to be a lingering fatigue from the vaccination. While it's not usual for me to feel tired at points throughout the day, I have been feeling a heavier and more full body fatigue than I usually experience. I have had to take naps more often, sometimes multiple times in a day.  During these bouts of fatigue, my whole body feels heavy and somewhat weak. It's similar to the exhausted feeling someone might have after they've been crying for a while but I haven't been crying or emotionally taxed in anyway.  Normally when I wake up in the morning, I might feel tired for the first 30 minutes to an hour but once I get moving, I feel better and more alter. I have been having a harder time feeling rested or awake in the mornings and even if I get more sleep than normal, I still feel exhausted. I did not change my routine or diet which I why I think this is related to the vaccine.
PRIOR_VAX: Arm pain at the injection site of a flu vaccine

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 47-year-old female presented for anaphylactic allergic reaction after getting her first dose of Covid19 vaccine.  Patient was initially seen by Dr., who then signed out to me pending observation and reevaluation.  In summary, patient had received total of 2 EpiPen 1 at home and 1 in the ED in conjunction with soluMedrol, Benadryl, and Pepcid.  Patient has history of anxiety and jittery as well as nervousness after epinephrine.  Patient was then given 1 mg p.o. Ativan for her symptom.     On my evaluation, patient is not in respiratory distress, She is still  Tachycardic in the 110s-120s  Which is likely from the EpiPen.  Patient stated that she normally stays tachycardic for a while after the epipen.  Patient otherwise not in respiratory distress, her posterior pharynx and her uvula is not swelling.  Patient also has no wheezing on auscultation exam.  We discussed the possibility of staying in the hospital under observation versus going home.  Patient reported she is back at baseline and would like to be discharged and I was in agreement with this plan. Patient does has 3 more epipen at home to use for worsening symptoms. She will be prescribed medrol dose pack. Red flags signs and symptoms were discussed with strict return instruction were given. Patient verbalized understanding and was in agreement with the plan. She was then discharged in stable condition.

Patient received Janssen COVID19 vaccine (LOT#1802068) at approximately 12:00 pm on 3/16/21. During the 15 minute observation period, she expressed "I don't feel good" and endorsed nausea. Shortly thereafter at approximately 12:10 pm, she started to slouch and nearly fainted while sitting in a chair. She did not fall or hit any part of her body. She was easily aroused with a touch on her arm and responded to verbal questions within seconds (less than a minute). She denied trouble breathing or chest pain. She then reported nausea again and was offered a receptacle to vomit in if needed; however, she did not vomit. Patient was encouraged and instructed to sit on the floor to prevent injury in case of fall but she refused stating that she didn't think she would be able to get back up given her preexisting knee problems. Pharmacy staff offered her water, a fan, and opened windows. Her jacket was removed in order to monitor blood pressure/ pulse, which was not abnormal. Patient did not have any trouble breathing, rash, swelling, abdominal cramps, or mental status changes. She was contacted via phone a few hours later for follow up on the incident, at which time she denied any issues and reported feeling well.
LAB_DATA: 03/16/21 blood pressure: 132/84 mmHg  03/16/21 heart rate: 80 bmp
OTHER_MEDS: Buspirone, sertraline, lamotrigine, calcium, vitamin D3, vitamin C, naproxen

I just wanted to pass along my vaccine experience.  So, I got the first dose on 25 Jan.  Within a day or two I developed a cold sore.  I had not had one in years but it wasn't a big deal.  I just figured the foreign vaccine had triggered it from being dormant.  Well, I got my second dose on 16 Feb.  Within days my eyes started feeling weird...specifically my left eye.  It was achy all day, red when I woke up, watery, and it was difficult to focus when I first turned on the lights.  This morning I went to the eye doctor and he told me that I had developed a blister (like a cold sore) in my eye.  I had never ever ever experienced this.  But like the first cold sore on my lip, he said it was dormant in my body and the vaccine just triggered it.  There are only two eye drops that treat this and they are pretty expensive but he told me that if I had not come to see him, this virus would have just lingered in my eye.  Just thought I would share my experience.
OTHER_MEDS: Citalipram, Zyrtec and Flonase as needed

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The first does, received on Saturday, January 9th, 2021, resulted in an, almost-immediate, reaction. Within, approximately 4 minutes of receiving the injection, I began to feel heat throughout, what felt like my bones (first in my neck, then down my body - arms & legs). I began to sweat, flush, had rapid heart beat, felt a. need to use the restroom ( which the RNs did not allow), and had elevated BP (166/105). The RN said she thought it was likely a vasovagal response, but once I. told them I had a shellfish allergy, they administered a shutoff Benadryl and called an ambulance who took me  to the ER. Once there, the ER doc saw I was flushing again and I was given two more doses of Benadryl (spread out of a few hours), I presume, as a precautionary measure. I was also given a Xanax, at my request, because I was very upset.   I had the second shot 2/14/2021 at a Hospital and had the heat feelings but no other reactions. I also made sure I was well hydrated, as I am sure I was severely dehydrated after the colonoscopy and surgery before the first dose.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Immediately upon receiving the shot I felt pain behind my left ear.  It continued throughout the next day whereupon I also started experiencing numbness on the left side of my face similar to getting a shot of Novocaine at the dentist.  As each day passed, the symptoms kept progressing across my face until my mouth is permanently skewed to the right.  It makes eating, drinking and speaking difficult.  Coincidentally the day after my vaccination, I had an appointment on Friday, March 12 at 10:30am for my first appointment with my new doctor.  I mentioned the ear pain (the numbness didn't start until that same afternoon) and she mentioned it wasn't uncommon for the lymph glands to be affected by the vaccination.  I assumed my symptoms would go away in a few days.  When they kept getting more pronounced, I sent her a couple of emails but she was out of the office until Tuesday, March 16.  Her assistant contacted me on Tuesday the 16th and told me to call 911 and go to the emergency room.  I drove myself to the Medical Group emergency room and was seen by the Dr.  After examining me, she also consulted with a neurologist and they diagnosed me with bell's palsy and said it would take between six to eight months to self correct.  She prescribed me Predisone 20mg dosage of three tablets once a day and Valacyclovir 1 gram dosage three times a day.  She also suggested I get some eye ointment to use at night and eye drops to be used four times a day since my left eye doesn't close all the way now.
OTHER_MEDS: Intermittent use of Airborne and Oscillococcinum.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I tested positive for COVID-19 on 12/16/20. I got my first shot (Moderna) on 1/28/21. The next day my right arm and my whole body hurt. After 24 hrs, I went back to normal. On 2/4/21, I went back to get my second dose of (Moderna). I didn't know I was not suppose to go 28 days later, since i only remember them telling me to go back on a Thursday at 3:30 PM. I gave my vaccine card to a lady in the registration table. She did not see my name on their roster, therefore she wrote my name on the bottom of her sheet. She then asked the pharmacist "Do you have a spot for one more?". I went and he asked me on which arm do I want the vaccine and I said the "right arm". I don't remember him telling me which vaccine I was going to receive.  He told me to wait outside in my car for 15 minutes. The next day both of  my arms started feeling numb.  I noticed that I received both vaccines (Moderna and Pfizer), when one of my coworkers asked me if I was ready to go and take the second dose on 2/22/21. That was when I checked my card and saw that I received both vaccines and my date for my second dose was on the back of my card 2/25/21. I called where I got the shot, and they said that they were not with the people in charge of giving the vaccines. I told my coworker to give them my number and tell them my situation, when she went to get her second dose (2/25/21). I never received a call from them. Staff from vaccine provider called me on 3/8/2021 to see if I wanted to schedule my second dose of Moderna. I had to explained my situation with her, since she did not know about it. She told me to go to my Family Doctor. I went to see him on 3/10/21. He said I will be ok and the symptoms will go away. He told me to take Claritin. I feel both of my arms less numb as of today. I hope this goes away soon. Other than that I feel healthy.

The adverse event started with discomfort in the arm, body aches, then progressed to headaches, more severe body aches, and chills.  Later in the day of 3/12/21, Patient began to spike a fever which eventually went to 102. He continually suffered from headaches, fatigue, body aches, and chills.  We attempted to control the symptoms with Tylenol. All symptoms continued on Saturday.  There was some minor control with Tylenol.  At approximately 9:30 am  patient had discomfort in his left underarm, when he lifted his arm, he became aware of a tennis ball size lump under his arm. Patient was suffering from severe lymphadenopathy in his left underarm and down the left side of his neck, with less severe but significant lymphadenopathy in the right underarm and down the right side of his neck.  Patient's fever continued to hover around 101 to 102 Saturday and Sunday. There were times, within an hour of taking Tylenol that it might drop to 99, but would go right back up.  He continued to experience fatigue, chills, etc... His fever finally broke on Monday morning and he is still experiencing some lymphadenopathy, but the lymph nodes are starting to reduce s of 3/17/21.
